<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish athletes are being recruited with the promise of a job as
the popularity of hurling and other Gaelic sports grows in this
country, immigration officials say.
   ``The new wave of Irish immigration has brought new life to
Gaelic games in this country,'' says Frank Costello, immigration
adviser to Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn and an ardent hurling fan.
   He says top young players are being recruited in Ireland with
promises of jobs. He tells of ``an entire village football squad
arriving from County Clare.''
   New York's Gaelic Athletic Association, according to past
president Terry Connaughton, now boasts 55 football teams, 16
hurling clubs and two camogie teams, a field sport for women.
   Sunday matches at Gaelic Park in New York City draw crowds of
4,000.
   A few seasons ago, two illegals, working as carpenters in the
Bronx, nipped home to help Galway defeat Kilkenny in the All
Ireland hurling championship, the Auld Sod's equivalent of the
Super Bowl.
