<HEAD>Irish-Language Writer Dead at 89</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seosamh Mac Grianna, who adapted simple
folk tales into Irish-language stories before virtually abandoning
writing 55 years ago, has died near his boyhood home. He was 89.
   Mac Grianna died in a hospital Monday in Letterkenny in
northwest Ireland, The Irish Times reported. Cause of death was not
given.
   Mac Grianna wrote his last book, ``Mo Bhealach Fein'' (My Own
Way), in 1935. Some of his most important work, thogh, was not
published until 1969. He entered a mental hospital in 1935 for
treatment of depression and wrote little afterward.
   ``Mac Grianna sought isolation, he was ready to accept the
reputation of being eccentric and unsociable, because he sought a
vision of which he could never speak,'' wrote critic Seamus Deane
in 1940 following the publication of ``Mo Bhealach Fein,'' a partly
fictionalized autobiography.
   Mac Grianna was born Joseph Green on Jan. 15, 1901, in an
Irish-speaking community in County Donegal. His family was known
for generations as storytellers, singers and poets.
   After leaving school, he taught school briefly and was involved
in the fight for Irish independence from Britain in the early
1920s, spending time in jail before becoming a full-time writer.
   As a young man, Mac Grianna contributed to newspapers and
periodicals and wrote several novels and short stories. He also
prepared Irish translations of a dozen books, including ``Ivanhoe''
and ``Ben Hur.''
   One of his best-known works, ``An Druma Mor'' (The Big Drum),
tells of an Irish community in the 1920s wrangling over a marching
band. It was not published until 1969.
   Two years later, it was awarded the Irish-American Butler prize
and became required reading in university Irish courses.
   In recent years, Mac Grianna had appeared at literary festivals.
   Mac Grianna was the brother of Seamus O Grianna, who wrote under
the name ``Maire'' and died in 1969.
   The Irish language, often called Gaelic, is spoken frequently
now by only about 5 to 10 percent of Ireland's 3.5 million people.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</TEXT>
