<HEAD>Ireland's First Woman President Takes Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland's first woman president, Mary
Robinson, was inaugurated today at Dublin Castle, and she extended
a hand of friendship to both Protestants and Catholics in
strife-ridden Northern Ireland.
   ``I will seek to encourage mutual understanding and tolerance
between all the different communities sharing this island,'' Mrs.
Robinson said in her acceptance speech, delivered in English and
Gaelic.
   A 21-gun salute echoed across the Irish capital as Mrs. Robinson
was sworn in by Chief Justice Thomas Finlay, following an
interdenominational service at the medieval, turreted castle.
   About 500 church and state dignitaries and Dublin-based foreign
diplomats looked on as Mrs. Robinson, wearing a purple jacket, took
the oath of office.
   Schools throughout the republic were given the day off to watch
the ceremony televised live in Britain and in the Irish Republic,
where Ireland's tricolor flags flew against cloudy skies.
   The president, a 46-year-old feminist lawyer, campaigned for the
largely ceremonial post on a liberal platform of change and a more
involved presidency. She won the Nov. 9 election with 52.8 percent
of the vote.
   She invited Irish descendants around the world to visit their
native island.
   Mrs. Robinson said she would continue Ireland's long tradition
of promoting international human rights, particularly in Latin
America and Africa, during her seven-year term in office.
   After her victory, Mrs. Robinson thanked the women of Ireland
who voted for her and ``instead of rocking the cradle, rocked the
system.''
   The president and mother of three children aged 9 to 18
addressed Irish women in her acceptance speech.
   ``As a woman I want women who have felt themselves outside
history to be written back into history ... finding a voice where
they have found a vision.''
   In 20 years in the Irish senate and as a lawyer, Mrs. Robinson
battled church and state in efforts to legalize divorce and
contraception.
   She won court cases to permit women to serve on juries, to
overturn laws criminalizing homosexuality, to restore inheritance
rights for illegitimate children and to give women legislators the
same pension rights as their male colleagues.
   Mrs. Robinson succeeds Patrick Hillery, who is stepping down
after the maximum 14 years in office.
</TEXT>
