<LEADPARA>  Weather Or Not; This week's springlike days certainly brought out our native
wildlife. Salt-lipped margarita-sippers returned to the outdoor tables at
Ixtapa in the downtown San Jose Pavilion. In newly reopened St. James Park,
the multi-stained lawn-sprawlers once again were snoozing in the sun. And at
homes around the valley, scores of suburban patio-setters took to their
chaises. Might as well enjoy. If it weren't for the drought, most people would
consider our weather too nice to complain about. . . . Debbie Perasso did get
a scare, though, when she turned on the kitchen faucet at her Almaden Valley
home and nothing came out. Seems her 4-year-old son, Brian, had been outside
playing with the house's main shut-off valve. "But," Perasso says, "I did
wonder for a while, 'What if we've actually run out?' " Remember the feeling,
Debbie. And see if you can share it with the water-wasters in the rest of the
state.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FAIR-WEATHER VALLEY FOWL WERE OUT IN FORCE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     WIDE, WIDE WHIRL -- The San Jose/Dublin Sister City Committee thinks big.
It has scheduled activities ranging from a March 7 dinner and poetry reading
with superstar poet Seamus Heaney to the annual Hibernians' dance March 17 for
Irish Week -- a "week" that lasts 11 days. . . . That also includes the
McEnery Cup Gaelic football game March 9 pitting San Jose against San
Francisco at PAL Stadium. Last year's little-publicized inaugural match at
Bellarmine College Prep saw San Francisco win 16-12, but now that you know
about this year's they figure PAL Stadium -- where I-280, I-680 and 101
converge -- should be about right to hold the crowds. Gaelic football, in case
you're not familiar, is a cross between soccer and rugby, played without
padding or helmets. (And then they go into politics?) . . . For the more
genteel, the daily English tea service that the San Jose Fairmont planned as a
pre-Valentine's Day promotion proved so popular that the hotel is keeping it
going. Cucumber sandwiches and scones with Devonshire cream, 3 to 5 p.m. daily
in the lobby lounge, and don't forget to curl that pinkie. . . . If it's
world-beat music you're after, San Jose's Bob Culbertson, a virtuoso on the
electric guitarlike Chapman stick, and his band, African Rain, will unveil
their new album Sunday at 7:30 p.m. at the Cactus Club. Emmett Chapman, who
has a certain vested interest, has said he'll be on hand. He's the Chapman
stick's inventor.;    EN-GULFED -- Distressing sight on I-880 near The Alameda
earlier this week: a large American flag blowing off the Toyota pickup to
which it had been attached, and following motorists swerving like crazy to
avoid running it over. If you're going to fly flags that way, folks, make sure
they're fastened securely so we don't start causing casualties here at home. .
. . Proprietors along Saratoga's restaurant row today are assembling goodies
to send to the Persian Gulf, a program Bill Carlson of Bella Mia calls "Taste
for the Troops." Good taste. . . . And Norma Strickland and Eva Yamamoto of In
Celebration, a San Jose gift basket service, promised to kick in $1 of each
pre-Valentine's Day sale toward gifts for our troops in the Middle East. The
gift baskets go on their way Monday, Strickland says: four pallets' worth.;   
LEST HE FORGET -- Leo Giorgetti thought he knew what all the ribbons on
automobiles were for -- red in opposition to drunk driving, white for people
against pornography, yellow for supporters of our troops in the Persian Gulf
-- but when his neighbor's car sprouted a chartreuse ribbon, the San Mateo
restaurateur had to ask. "It doesn't stand for anything," the neighbor
replied, "except I'm supposed to buy a gallon of milk on my way home from
work."  </TEXT>
