<TEXT>
   Thomas Flanagan is a professor of English at the State University of New York at Stony Brook, an authority on early 19th-century Irish fiction, whose first novel, "The Year of the French," appeared nine years ago to high praise. 
Its success seemed so much a function of its inimitability that one turns with both hope and trepidation to Mr. Flanagan's new book, an uncommonly long, earnest, learned historical novel bearing the somewhat windy title "The Tenants of Time" (Dutton, 824 pages, $21.95). 

   As before, rather than serving up potted index cards, bodice-ripping or psychopolitical sermonettes, Mr. Flanagan is uncompromising in his ambition to write a realistic -- and manifestly literary -- historical novel. 
He may skillfully employ the multiple narrative techniques of Conrad, but he doesn't attempt the modernistic symphonies of Faulkner or the surreal orchestral scherzos of Pynchon. 
He brings a seriousness to his work that cannot fail to elicit admiration. 

   His subject could not be grander: the tortured history of Ireland from the abortive Fenian Rising of 1867 to the fall of Parnell in 1891. 
A young Oxford graduate comes to Southwest Ireland in 1904 to examine the connections between two incidents in local history that might illuminate the inner logic of a bloody quarter century. 
He consults two complementary witnesses -- an antiquarian schoolmaster and a belle lettristic aristocrat. 
Their narratives lead him into the world of a little market town and its castle, and the narrators multiple. 

   He learns of four friends -- the schoolmaster, his cousin (a fanatic Irish nationalist), a shop clerk who becomes a lawyer and member of Parliament, and a local playboy "all froth and banter, silver flasks and flowered waistcoats, chat about women and horses." 
In their 20s they take the Fenian oath to free Ireland from British rule. 
With 60 other ragtag nationalists they attempt to seize the local police barracks on March 6, 1867, when all of Ireland is supposed to rise in the Fenians' "patchwork conspiracy." 
They fail: British troops round them up in the neighboring Clonbrony Wood and try them for treason. 
The schoolmaster and the clerk serve six months; the fanatic seven years; the playboy is let off altogether. 
But the four pass from squalid fact into legend; they become "the heroes of Clonbrony Wood," the subject of ballad, fantasy, propaganda. 

   Over the years their paths diverge: The playboy chases foxes and women, the schoolmaster collects Gaelic folklore, the clerk becomes a brilliant (and convincingly depicted) politician, and the revolutionary continues to plot murder and mayhem in the New York Irish community and then, undercover, back in Dublin and London. 
He figures in the infamous Phoenix Park murders of 1882 and in an attempt to blow up London Bridge in 1884. 

   As the clerk becomes a member of Parliament and loyal lieutenant of the most glamorous Irish patriot of the age, Charles Stewart Parnell (the "uncrowned king"), the terrorist slowly becomes drenched in blood. 
When Parnell is destroyed in 1891 -- on what seems the very eve of victory for Home Rule for Ireland -- by the revelation of his adultery with Kitty O'Shea, the clerk and the terrorist realize their own bright hopes have crashed, and they struggle to accommodate the hideous facts of the present with their fantasies of the past. 
The end of the story obliges them in the grimmest possible fashion. 
Betrayal and murder link the four again in the fields that run toward Clonbrony Wood. 

   But there's more. 
As this political tale unfolds, we also learn of life up at the castle -- of the earl who becomes an amateur impressionist painter, of his cousin who writes historical romances, and of his seductively independent wife whose love affair with the clerk-turned-politician links castle and town and -- of course -- provides an instructive parallel to the tale of adulterous Parnell. 
This novel is nothing if not intensely plotted. 

   The more than 100 characters we meet are carefully noted and their voices are in handsome supply, though they do tend toward a certain mellifluous homogeny. 
This must be an occupational hazard for a writer dealing with Ireland. 
How can one avoid such bits of local color as "the kettle above the fire was kept at the boil, and the tea itself was strong enough to trot a mouse across it, in lantern light the color of mahogany." 
At every hand lie the temptations of the set piece: "A farmhouse is best for weddings, with the barrels of stout and porter wheeled in from the barn, and a fiddler to lean against the wall, the notes moving like quicksilver, in air heavy with tobacco smoke, the smell of food, drink spilled upon rough board or close-packed earth." 

   As one breasts the current of this sometimes creamy, sometimes awkward self-regarding style (it's obviously catching), one inevitably thinks of death by drowning. 
Never fear. 
The same remarkable will that created this admirably unremitting historical narrative will carry us safely to the sounding shore. 
It's quite a remarkable performance. 

   ---
   Mr. Locke teaches English and comparative literature at Columbia University. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

