<HEAD>Soldier Arrested After Civilian Shot To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British soldier was arrested
today after he fatally shot a civilian in the back as the man
walked to a football match, the army said.
   The army said the soldier was in an observation tower Sunday at
a permanent military checkpoint a half-mile from the Irish border.
   From the tower he took a shot at the man, Aidan McAnespie, who
was walking to a weekly Gaelic football game in the village of
Aughnacloy, County Tyrone.
   The 23-year-old died on the road before medical aid or a priest
could reach him, police said.
   Police said the soldier was arrested and was being interrogated.
Villagers said McAnespie belonged to the Roman Catholic minority in
the British-ruled, Protestant-majority province.
   The army said it ``deeply regrets'' the incident. It gave no
other information and did not identify the soldier.
   ``It was cold-blooded murder _ I saw McAnespie shot in the
back,'' said Anthony McGonnell, a councilman.
   Francis Molloy, another councilman, said McAnespie was an
election worker for Sinn Fein, political arm of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army fighting British rule.
   Molloy said McAnespie claimed to have been repeatedly harassed
and threatened by the security forces.
   ``He said he was afraid the security forces would carry out
their threats,'' Molloy said.
   The shooting further strained relations between Britain and the
Irish Republic government in Dublin. Dublin called immediately for
details of the killing.
   The Irish government, which regards itself as responsible for
the Catholic minority in the north, has been angered by two recent
developments.
   The British Court of Appeal recently upheld the convictions of
six Irishmen jailed for life for two bombings that killed 21 people
on the British mainland in 1974. The Irish Republican Army claimed
responsibility for the blasts.
   Britain also decided not to prosecute any Northern Ireland
police officers connected with the police shootings of six unarmed
Catholics in an alleged ``shoot-to-kill'' policy against guerrilla
suspects.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the province with the Irish Republic, which is predominantly
Roman Catholic.
</TEXT>
