<HEAD>Dublin Government To Launch Own Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former parish priest of an
Irish nationalist who was shot dead from an army observation tower
said Monday that police and soldiers harrassed the victim for
several years.
   British officials said they have launched an investigation into
the incident Sunday in Northern Ireland near the Irish border. But
in Dublin, the Irish government announced it will hold its own
probe headed by the deputy Irish police chief.
   McAnespie's death came at a time of severe strain in Anglo-Irish
relations over other incidents involving the police and the
province's Catholic minority.
   The Rev. Brendan McHugh said Aidan McAnespie had to cross the
Irish border daily to go to work and was constantly harassed at the
army checkpoint.
   ``We complained time out of number to the police and military,
but no action was ever taken. Life for the poor man had just become
unbearable,'' he told reporters.
   The army said it ``deeply regrets'' the shooting. It said
23-year-old McAnespie was hit by a bullet fired from an army
observation post about half a mile from the Irish border in County
Tyrone.
   Police said the soldier involved was in military custody while
an investigation was launched. No details about the soldier were
given. Police declined to comment on the priest's allegations of
harassment.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said
security sources reported that the soldier involved told detectives
a machine gun was accidentally discharged as he handed it to
another soldier.
   The agency also quoted unidentified sources as saying three
strike marks were found on the roadway near the victim, indicating
three shots might have been fired.
   McAnespie's brother-in-law, Paul McCabe, said of the
investigation announced by the Dublin government: ``We welcome any
attempt to bring the murderer of Aidan to real justice and ensure
that there is not yet another cover-up.
   ``Maybe at this late stage the Irish government will finally
recognize the reality of families like ourselves having to put up
with constant harassment. ... In the light of recent developments
of incidents here (in Northern Ireland) I do not think anyone would
be prepared to give evidence to the RUC.''
   The RUC _ Royal Ulster Constabulary _ is Northern Ireland's
police force. Its policemen are frequent targets of Irish
Republican Army gunmen and bombers. Allegations that the RUC tried
to thwart an investigation into the slaying of six unarmed
Catholics by an RUC unit in 1982 has intensified the deep hostility
among many Catholics toward the force.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite the province with
the Irish Republic, which is predominantly Roman Catholic.
   Relatives said McAnespie was walking to a regular weekly Gaelic
football game in the Northern Ireland village of Aughnacloy, County
Tyrone, when he was shot. He had passed through the checkpoint,
which lies on the route to the football ground.
   Francis Molloy, a local councilman, said McAnespie was an
election worker for Sinn Fein, political arm of the IRA. The IRA
denied McAnespie was among their members.
   McHugh said McAnespie was never involved in paramilitary
activity but was harassed nevertheless.
   ``He was never abused physically, just verbally, and his car was
often taken apart,'' McHugh said, referring to vehicle searches.
``I don't know why he was singled out for such treatment.''
   ``The campaign against him must have been going on for at least
five years. Other young lads were also stopped, but Aidan appeared
to be getting special treatment,'' he said.
   Last month Britain provoked Irish outrage by saying it will not
prosecute policemen accused of perverting the course of justice in
the aftermath of the killing of six unarmed Catholics in three
incidents in late 1982.
   The strain was compounded by a British appeals court's refusal
to overturn the conviction of six Irishmen accused of perpetrating
twin bombings that killed 21 people in 1974. Many Irish officials
and civilians believe the six are victims of a miscarriage of
justice.
</TEXT>
