<HEAD>Ireland Probes Ulster Shooting; Soldier in 1983 Shooting Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British soldier ordered
jailed for life for killing a Belfast Roman Catholic has been freed
and returned to his regiment after serving only three years in
prison, the army said today.
   The disclosure came amid Anglo-Irish tensions following the
killing of a Catholic man on Sunday by a British soldier and the
Irish government's decision to conduct its own investigation of the
slaying, which occurred in Northern Ireland.
   The announcement that the convicted killer, Pvt. Ian Richard
Thain, was back in uniform, although not in Northern Ireland,
provoked sharp reactions from leaders of the province's Catholic
minority. At the same time, leaders of Northern Ireland's
Protestant majority were angered by Dublin's announcement that it
will probe Sunday's killing.
   Thain was jailed for the fatal shooting of Thomas Reilly, road
manager of the pop group Bananarama, on Aug. 9, 1983. Thain claimed
in court that he fired because riots were going on and he believed
Reilly was about to pull a gun on him.
   But the judge found him ``deliberately untruthful'' and said he
did not believe Thain truly feared Reilly was about to shoot at
him. Thain was the first soldier sentenced to life imprisonment for
actions in Northern Ireland.
   An army statement said Thain was then 18 and ``while the army in
no way condones his action, we consider the incident to have been a
tragic error of judgment made by a young man in very difficult
circumstances.''
   The Home Office said Thain was released on a life license, a
form of parole whereby he can be reimprisoned ``should his behavior
give rise to concern.'' It said he was freed after a review by the
state parole board.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, said Thain's release showed there was no justice
in Northern Ireland. The victim's father, Jim Reilly, said: ``I'm
very, very shocked and distressed. I can't believe this has
happened.''
   Meanwhile, the Irish government sent Deputy Police Commissioner
Eugene Crowley to Monaghan, on the border with Northern Ireland, to
launch an investigation into Sunday's shooting of 23-year-old Aidan
McAnespie.
   McAnespie was killed by a bullet from an army observation tower
at a checkpoint near Aughnacloy, half a mile from the frontier in
County Tyrone.
   Relatives said he was walking to a weekly Gaelic football game
and had passed through the checkpoint when he was shot.
   McAnespie was a Sinn Fein supporter, and his former parish
priest said he was harassed whenever he passed through the
checkpoint. Press Association, the British news agency, said the
soldier who fired at McAnespie told his interrogators it was an
accident. The soldier is in military custody.
   The Irish move was seen as a calculated slight to Britain, since
its police force in the province was conducting an inquiry. British
authorities stressed that the Irish investigation would be confined
to Ireland's side of the border.
</TEXT>
