<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   She Puts Celtic Fringe on Country Music Charts
   ----
   By James Ring Adams
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<LP>
   Just hours before winning a Grammy, country singer Kathy
Mattea reminisced about her first meeting two years earlier
with her current musical hero. "We went to the show and we
were doing the whole bit about trying to get backstage. It
was such a role reversal," she said. "I felt like a groupie."
   Ms. Mattea, one of the hottest names in Nashville, wasn't
trying to crash the dressing room of a country music great
like George Jones or Loretta Lynn. The musician she was so
eager to meet was an obscure Scottish folk singer named
Dougie McLean.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ms. Mattea described her backstage visit as a musical
turning point. She and her husband escorted Mr. McLean around
Nashville the next day and the following year paid him a
return visit in the Scottish lowlands. Mr. McLean's quietly
passionate Scottish traditionalism permeates her latest
album. While downing a club sandwich on the day of the Grammy
awards, she pushed aside thoughts of her impending award in
her enthusiasm for his music. When they parted company in
Nashville, she said, "I burst into tears. There was so much
more I wanted to say."
   Ms. Mattea isn't the only one in Nashville who is finding
a lot to say to spiritual cousins across the water.
Performers who have brought new vigor to American country
music by returning to its old-time roots recognize their
counterparts in the musical revival sweeping Europe's "Celtic
fringe." From Scotland's Outer Hebrides to the Britanny
Peninsula in France, young performers are finding an
international audience for an eclectic mix of very old tunes
and very pop styles. Popular groups such as DeDannan, the
Tannahill Weavers and Kornog perform ancient songs in Gaelic,
Erse and Breton side by side with original folk and
rock-tinged compositions, and their taste in instrumentation
is omnivorous. The distinctive combination of hard-driving
rhythm and aching melody stands a thousand miles closer to
the Celtic heart than the "green trash" of the St. Patrick's
Day beer bust.
   American country music itself grows out of Scots-Irish
roots, so maybe it's not surprising that the two movements
would intersect. What is remarkable is the intense emotion
that the contact arouses in some of Nashville's leading
performers.
   Ricky Skaggs, a former Country Music Association
Entertainer of the Year, has warm memories of a visit to
Dublin's Society to Preserve Irish Folk Music. "Even the
flavor of the food tasted so much like being at home in
eastern Kentucky," he says. "The music was much alike. We
didn't want to leave them."
   Folk-influenced country singers such as Emmylou Harris and
Nanci Griffith made the Irish pilgrimage in recent years,
bringing back material for their albums. Even pop superstar
Dolly Parton, a far more richly faceted talent than her
marketing would indicate, startled a recent interviewer by
confessing to a secret urge to spend a month in Ireland.
   The traffic is two-way. On a trip to Erin, the bluegrass
banjo star Bela Fleck befriended a soprano from County Clare
named Maura O'Connell and helped persuade her to settle in
Nashville. With a haunting bluesy voice once featured with
the Irish folk-revival group DeDannan, Ms. O'Connell cut two
albums with Warner Bros. This year, she received a Grammy
nomination in the contemporary folk category. Other Irish
singers are following. Mary Black, another lead vocalist with
DeDannan, recently signed with Curb Records. Daniel
O'Donnell, who has placed seven albums at once on the U.K.
top 20, is Britain's leading native country singer. He has
begun recording in Nashville with Ms. Mattea's producer and
starts a major American tour next month. American country
music in general finds its strongest following in the U.K. in
the Celtic regions.
   Even before they began to migrate, the musicians were
learning from each other. Growing up in a family of Irish
fishmongers, Ms. O'Connell was so inundated by traditional
music that she got sick of it, and started her career singing
Bonnie Raitt blues covers. She says she began to rediscover
her roots when she heard Emmylou Harris, the high priestess
of American traditionalism, on an Irish tour.
   But fans have done even more than the musicians to bring
Celtic music to America. Wendy Newton of Weston, Conn.,
visited Ireland 16 years ago and was smitten by the fiddle
music she heard one afternoon in a pub. Returning home, she
started the independent Green Linnet label to distribute
Irish records in the U.S. Her roster now includes many of the
best known Celtic groups, such as Ireland's Altan and
Scotland's Tannahill Weavers and Silly Wizard.
   Perhaps no one has spread the Celtic revival further,
however, than Fiona Ritchie, originator of the weekly
National Public Radio program "Thistle &amp; Shamrock." Her
lilting half-brogue has introduced thousands not only to the
Irish and Scottish music of the title, but to the Celtic
sounds of Brittany and French Canada. A former exchange
student at the University of North Carolina in Charlotte, Ms.
Ritchie started the program for the local public radio in
1983. It is now broadcast on 223 stations. Ms. Ritchie also
brought Ms. Mattea face to face with her hero, Mr. McLean.
   Ms. Mattea fell in love with the music years before when a
friend lent her one of Mr. McLean's hard-to-find tapes.
Through a music journalist she met in London, she sent word
that if Mr. McLean ever came to the U.S., he'd find a fan in
Nashville. Several months later, Ms. Ritchie called with news
that Mr. McLean and fellow performers on his independent
Dunkeld Records label were coming to town on a tour organized
by "Thistle &amp; Shamrock." Ms. Mattea not only got to meet Mr.
McLean, she and her husband, Grammy-winning songwriter Jon
Vezner, provided tour buses for the last leg of his trip.
   Mr. McLean left them with an invitation to visit Scotland,
and Ms. Mattea took it up at her first chance. "We had no
idea if they were going to think, `Oh God, the crazy
Americans are coming across the ocean,'" she said. "But they
were just great." Their collaboration "just sort of
happened," she said, "because we were there."
   Ms. Mattea and her husband found themselves helping Mr.
McLean prepare a local music festival called "Event in a
Tent." "Dougie and Jon were out two days before the festival
happened, digging the hole for the loo with a backhoe," Ms.
Mattea recalled.
   "In the rain," added Mr. Vezner.
   Ms. Mattea was thoroughly charmed by the simplicity of
life in Mr. McLean's native Perthshire, in the Scottish
lowlands. "It was the way people ought to live," she said.
Like other pilgrims to the Celtic lands, she was also deeply
impressed by the uncommercial approach to the music. "We'd be
talking about some instrument," she said of a recording
session at Dunkeld, "and Dougie would put it in my hands and
say, well, go play this. In Nashville, so many times, we
would just send for the percussionist.
   "It gave me a much more organic kind of involvement with
the record," she said. "When I got back to Nashville, I found
I was much less intimidated. I was able to express my own
vision better."
   The influence shines through Ms. Mattea's remarkable new
album, "Time Passes By" (PolyGram). She performs with Mr.
McLean on one of his own songs, inspired by his grandfather's
work as a fisherman. They pull out all the stops on a Celtic
setting of Julie Gold's "From a Distance," bringing in
Highland pipes, bodhran and digeridoo. (The latter, the root
of an Australian gum tree hollowed out by ants, is actually
an aborigine instrument, but in Mr. McLean's hands, its
"grumbly buzz" melds nicely with the beloved drone of the
bagpipe.) Even cuts done in Nashville show the impact of the
Scottish sojourn. They startle the listener with an unadorned
passion contrasting sharply with the standard Music Row
product.
   The album breaks the Nashville mold to the extent that Ms.
Mattea at first worried about its reception. But after two
weeks it's No. 27 on Billboard's country music chart and
rising. Apparently the Celtic fringe is a nice addition to
her rhinestone suit.
   ---
   Mr. Adams writes frequently about country music.
</TEXT>
