<HEAD>Thatcher Rebukes Ireland over Shooting Inquiry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher rebuked Ireland on Tuesday for
conducting its own investigation of the death of a man killed by a
gunshot from a British army observation post just inside Northern
Ireland.
   The prime minister said she did ``not think it right or
possible'' under the 1985 Anglo-Irish agreement for the Irish
Republic to investigate the shooting Sunday of Aidan McAnespie, 23,
in the British province.
   During the House of Commons question-and-answer period, she
declared: ``The Irish government can inquire into anything they
wish, but not of course into matters north of the border.'' The
Anglo-Irish accord gives Ireland an advisory role in the Northern
Ireland affairs in an effort to redress grievances of Roman
Catholics in the Protestant-dominated province.
   Mrs. Thatcher's remarks appeared likely to worsen relations,
already strained by disputes that include Britain's refusal to
prosecute police officers involved in the shooting deaths of six
unarmed Catholics in 1982.
   The British army also disclosed Tuesday that a soldier given
life in prison for the shooting death of a Catholic in Belfast had
been freed and returned to his regiment after serving three years.
   Reports that Pvt. Ian Richard Thain was back in uniform,
although not in Northern Ireland, provoked sharp responses from
leaders of the province's Catholic minority.
   Thain was convicted of fatally shooting Thomas Reilly, road
manager of the pop group Bananarama, on Aug. 9, 1983. He claimed in
court that he fired because riots were going on and he believed
Reilly was about to pull a gun.
   The judge found him ``deliberately untruthful.'' Thain was the
first soldier sentenced to life in prison for actions in Northern
Ireland.
   An army statement said Thain was 18 at the time and, ``while the
army in no way condones his action, we consider the incident to
have been a tragic error of judgment made by a young man in very
difficult circumstances.''
   The Home Office said Thain was released on a life license, a
form of parole under which he can be returned to prison ``should
his behavior give rise to concern.''
   A security cordon ringed the town of Aughnacloy for McAnespie's
funeral Tuesday. He was buried across the border in the Irish
Republic.
   The Irish government sent Eugene Crowley, deputy police
commissioner, to the border town of Monaghan to investigation
McAnespie's death. Protestant politicans called the Irish inquiry
unwarranted interference by a foreign government in Northern
Ireland's affairs.
   McAnespie supported Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the
outlawed Irish Republican Army. He was killed by a bullet from a
British army observation tower at a checkpoint near Aughnacloy in
County Tyrone, half a mile from the border.
   Relatives said he was walking to a weekly Gaelic football game
and had passed through the checkpoint.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said the
soldier told interrogators the shooting was an accident. He was in
military custody Tuesday.
